<item>
            <title>[LU-19700] Reliable way to keep MGS NID tables in-sync with targets</title>
                <link>https://jira.whamcloud.com/browse/LU-19700</link>
                <project id="10000" key="LU">Lustre</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;this is continuation of &lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.whamcloud.com/browse/LU-19692&quot; title=&quot;MGS NID tables are lost after failover and need to be rebuilt&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;LU-19692&quot;&gt;LU-19692&lt;/a&gt; and is related to &lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.whamcloud.com/browse/LU-10360&quot; title=&quot;use Imperative Recovery logs for client-&amp;gt;MDT/OST connections&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;LU-10360&quot;&gt;LU-10360&lt;/a&gt;/&lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.whamcloud.com/browse/LU-10359&quot; title=&quot;remove NIDs from config llogs&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;LU-10359&quot;&gt;LU-10359&lt;/a&gt;. Right now IR itself is not reliable, it might improve recovery but not must and that is by design. If we are going to rely on IR to discover target NIDs then it should be improved to keep NID tables on MGS in valid state all the time. Right now NID tables are built when target starts and registers with MGS and when target network is changed. If MGS itself restarts all NID tables are gone and must be restored, which is solved by &lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.whamcloud.com/browse/LU-19692&quot; title=&quot;MGS NID tables are lost after failover and need to be rebuilt&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;LU-19692&quot;&gt;LU-19692&lt;/a&gt;, but it is still one time event at target side.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;MGS itself should check that NID tables instances are consistent with its own instance after restart and ask targets for update if needed, especially when NID tables are read by client&lt;/p&gt;</description>
